A Telegram MCP server is a software bridge that allows AI assistants like Claude, Cursor, or Windsurf to interact with your personal Telegram account using the MTProto protocol instead of the restricted Bot API [1][2][3]. By acting as a userbot, these servers grant your AI full access to your private messages, contacts, media, and group management features [1][4][5].

Multiple implementations exist, such as mcp-telegram and others [1][4][6][5], generally requiring you to authenticate your account—often via QR code or session strings—before exposing tools for tasks like searching dialogs, sending or deleting messages, and downloading media [1][4][2][5]. Most implementations provide local stdio or HTTP transport options to integrate with your MCP-compatible client configuration [6][5][7][8].

For example, to configure a standard stdio-based server in your Claude Desktop configuration file:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "telegram": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "mcp-telegram"]
    }
  }
}
```

Consult the documentation for your chosen repository, as specific setup commands and tool sets vary by implementation [1][6][7].
